-- Japan, India, South Korea, Malaysia, Thailand: Asia Bond, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-12-08T22:22:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-08/japan-india-south-korea-malaysia-thailand-asia-bond-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Bank of Japan board member  Yoshihisa Morimoto  will
speak at an economic forum in Saitama City at 10:30 a.m. He will
also speak at a press conference at 2 p.m. Chief Cabinet
Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold media briefings at 11 a.m.
and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Cabinet Office will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
final figures for the nation’s gross domestic product in the
third quarter. Japan’s economy grew an annualized 4.1 percent in
the period, according to a Bloomberg News survey.  The Finance Ministry will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on Japanese and foreign investment flows for domestic and
overseas securities during the week ended Dec. 3.  The Ministry of Finance will sell 2.4 trillion yen ($28.6
billion) of five-year bonds today. The ministry will announce a
coupon for the new securities at 10:30 a.m.  The yield on the 1.2 percent government bond due December
2020 was 1.23 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 84.01 per dollar at 7:09 a.m. in Tokyo.  India: The government will report food inflation for the
week ended Nov. 27. An index measuring wholesale prices of
agricultural products including lentils, rice and vegetables
increased 8.6 percent from a year earlier the previous week, the
smallest gain since April 2009.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.11
percent. The rupee was at 45.08.  Malaysia: The Department of Statistics will report the
country’s balance of payments figures for the third quarter. The
data showed a surplus of $16.2 billion in the previous three
months, the smallest amount since 2004.  The statistics department will say industrial production
rose 2.2 percent in October, according to a Bloomberg survey of
economists before today’s report. It gained 5.6 percent the
previous month, the most since June.  Bank Negara Malaysia will sell 80 million ringgit ($25.4
million) of 91-day notes and 100 million ringgit of 364-day
Islamic bills.  The yield on the 3.835 percent note due August 2015 was
3.36 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was at
3.1445.  South Korea: The Bank of Korea will keep the benchmark
interest rate unchanged today at 2.5 percent, according to all
10 economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  The central bank will also release producer price index
data for November. The gauge rose 5 percent from a year earlier
in October, the biggest gain since 2008.  The yield on the 3 percent security due in December 2013
was 3.08 percent. The won traded at 1,141.15.  Taiwan: Taiwan’s central bank will auction NT$40 billion
($1.3 billion) of 10-year bonds.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due in September 2020
was 1.45 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$30.706.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will report foreign-exchange
reserves for the week ended Dec. 3. Reserves dropped in each of
the three previous weeks, retreating from a record $172.2
billion on Nov. 5 to total $168.2 billion on Nov. 26.  The University of the Thai Chamber of Commerce will report
consumer confidence figures for November. The index fell to 71.6
in the previous month, the first drop in six months.  The Bank of Thailand will sell 80 billion baht ($2.7
billion) of 14-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.67
percent. The baht was at 30.13.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at   fyoon2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at   shendry@bloomberg.net . 